The first virtual provider is already coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, and the Czech service providers offer virtually all services, as they are offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, there is something missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classic at lower prices.
Maybe this one won't be waiting long.
The fact that Czech mobile operators are the most expensive in Europe, we have often reported on Mobil.cz.
This was also confirmed by the telecommunications authority ČTÓ, which pointed out that the price of a text is higher here than in the rest of the European Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation is likely to arise - for some customers of Czech mobile operators SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How come prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really makes a fight announcement.
It may sound paradoxical, but in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of far more than 100%.
On the other hand, mobile operators like to be ashamed that there is an extremely high level of competition in the Czech market.
The President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTì) Pavel Dvořák, who had often said in the past that there was no room for another provider in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that a classic provider with its own network no longer has a lot of opportunities (by the way, he would probably not find any more frequencies).
But there is another possibility - a virtual provider.
In particular, the entry of virtual providers into the mobile market resulted in a significant price reduction, to which the classic mobile operators also had to respond.
There were similar voices to those in the Czech Republic before such companies, such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile, entered the market in the UK.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can really be successful.
By the way, you don't have to look for examples for long.
In February of this we reported on the launch of the virtual mobile provider in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider managed to win more than 100 thousand customers and thus become the five largest provider in the country.
The Penta financial group, which has, among other things, U: fon in the Czech Republic, is behind mobile.
The advantage of virtual providers is that you can focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order to work effectively, virtual providers need much less customers than a classic provider.
They do not need relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, the virtual providers usually benefit as low-cost companies - they offer cheap phone calls and SMS, but this is often accompanied by a less extensive service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers SMS in the UK at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of mobile learning in Poland shows, it can also be a pretty good move to put on a non-cliché target group.
This provider is specifically aimed at men.
"Real guys choose mobile - the provider they like and can trust," says David Seibert, CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator company of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept to that in Poland could be found in the Czech Republic.
The press speaker of Vodafone Miroslav Čepický also doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
It is also relatively saturated from the point of view of the service offer. "
In the Czech Republic, mobile telephone operators think
But it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile service provider conquers the Czech Republic, this will not be mobile.
"We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look particularly hopeful.
There will be more to a market entry of mobile services in other countries of our region, "says in a phone call for mobile.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to do so.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything they can to ensure that no potential competitor is created.
Their interest in the launch of a virtual mobile service provider has been showing for a long time the GTS Novera group, which wants to take a further step to become a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed network but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them we have already been able to make progress in the negotiations, "said the press speaker of the Pavel Kaidl group.
Maybe we'll have better times now.
Non-official information shows that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
But so far this is surrounded by an invincible wall of silence.
"At this moment, we do not assume that there is room for a full virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market has large specific features in relation to other markets.
So far, no subject has addressed us with a complex and serious project in this area, "says in his statement for Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sršeň from the press department of Telefónica O2.
Other suppliers also point to the specific features of the Czech market.
The press speaker of T-Mobile Martina Kemrová adds in rare agreement with the O2 statement: "We have not yet found a viable and mutually beneficial project to build on."
And it adds: "In the network of T-Mobile, hardly a virtual provider will appear by the end of the year.
At this moment, we should already have a concrete offer to think so in the short term. "
Vodafone is more focused on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický means: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of cost and infrastructure sharing.
This is precisely what we consider best from the customer's point of view.
The main strategy of Vodafone in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile Internet. "
The responsible authorities - with the providers hand in hand
The approach of mobile operators is easy to understand, another is more competitive, which would lead to lower prices and thus to a fall in profits.
So why should such a competitor be easier to enter the market?
The fact that the providers can draw a line when it comes to something also proves the long back and back of the creation of U: fon.
The most powerful pressure in the direction of ČTů was now from the company T-Mobile, when you: fon came on the market.
This is also demonstrated by the publicly available information from the ČTț websites.
But now you are right: fon as an argument why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová noted: "The competitive field of the mobile market has also recently been strengthened by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile service provider.
Taking into account the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that a new player would make high demands on the market itself and, above all, its services. "
However, in view of this approach by mobile operators, the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities is surprising.
This is not just the attitude of ČTÄ which, unfortunately, in the Czech Republic - in contrast to the United Kingdom and other highly developed countries - does not have the power to intervene in economic competition.
It has only the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
This, however, referred to this whole problem in its very typical position.
"The entry into the market of a virtual mobile operator would be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile telephone provider and a virtual provider on the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such contract has been concluded, because the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for the classic suppliers, "said Kristián Chalupa of the ÚOHS External Relations Department.
Such a formulation would not be surprised by the representatives of the suppliers.
This is more than a concern from an authority that is responsible for the interests of consumers and, among other things, to ensure that no one uses their position on the market.
In particular, if Kristián Chalupa adds: "In a foreign country, where virtual providers work quite normally, it is observed that their entry into the market has contributed to a reduction in the price of mobile telephone services."
However, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market and a price reduction are probably not one of the interests of the ÚOHS.
In this case, the almost already existing agreement between the three mobile operators, which results from their reactions, is really shocking.
The question of whether it is really just a coincidence is obvious.
Just as the absolutely same petrol price at the gas stations is certainly only a coincidence and the result of a hard competition.
"The Authority has not found any evidence in this case that indicates any action against competition, and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the suppliers have a dominant market position, so they do not have the appropriate increased responsibility for their actions on the market.
The necessary instruments to open the mobile market to virtual providers are probably also missing from the telecommunications regulatory authority, "said Chalupa in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, prepared by ČTì, according to which telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile operators have a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - the agreement of the network operator is always necessary for the entry into the market of a virtual provider.
And the mobile telephone provider has - logically - the monopoly for its network.
This means that it necessarily takes a dominant position in a particular segment.
However, even if you do not go along with this argument, it should at least be a warning for the ÚOHS that three mobile operators are acting in a similar way.
In this respect, complaints from a number of interested parties (including the company GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles in negotiations with all suppliers.
The transfer of responsibility to ČTÓ is then a very common trick in telecommunications services, with which the ÚOHS disregards itself from the whole issue.
This was already observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recent amendment of the Telecommunications Act has not been able to implement the extension of the ČT's powers to economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of experts have promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS only need to know that too well, but they probably have other interests.
It's all right when no one looks
The operation of any pseudo-virtual provider, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks, is not taken into account.
They are companies that issue their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but they are only partly public.
They are usually companies that operate in the field of multilevel marketing.
For example, mobile phone services offer Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies usually only come to the chosen ones.
The joke of the thing is that the company appears to the operator as a classic company, which orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer he will then receive special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar resale.
"If there are cases that you describe, it may be an infringement of the contractual conditions with which we will then deal, which may lead to an end to cooperation with the relevant society," Martina Kemrová answered our question on this issue.
However, it is quite unlikely that such a thing will not be discussed with the operators of mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned above, they can be thousands of customers.
However, no operator is opposed to such an approach.
In fact, they do not have negligible profits from the activities of these companies, at the same time they are not affected by the actual official marketing, in contrast to the actual virtual providers.
Miroslav Čepický draws attention to possible problems: "The law allows such types of speculation, despite all this, the services of these companies are used by a very small percentage of customers.
They must also accept that the SIM card does not run on their phone, so they cannot fully have the same as the normal customers of the mobile phone providers. "
This alone, however, should at least seem strange to the ČTì.
There is also another question for the ÚOHS.
If the mobile telephone providers close their eyes before such a procedure, why are they blocking themselves from a virtual provider?
It is to be added that the ÚOHS has quite strong powers to detect such activities, and if it does not want it, it does not have to be satisfied with the statement by the suppliers that they do not know about it and their terms and conditions would prohibit it.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As has been pointed out several times in the text, the entry of virtual providers has brought a significant decrease in the price of the various services.
In this context, in virtually all countries where virtual providers have been created, the classic suppliers have tried to prevent their emergence from being practically more or less.
The arguments they used were practically identical - a too small, or too saturated market, problems in the quality of services, etc.
In the advanced countries, however, the regulatory bodies, which did not try to protect the interests of mobile operators, but their customers, were involved in these moments.
Whether it is through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator was created and followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies are throwing themselves at the whole case like a hot potato.
Based on our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that ambiguity in the skills in these cases is more than favourable.
But let's not throw the gun in the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider is soon to emerge, the Czech mobile market may soon get back on the move.
If a provider allows the creation of a virtual mobile service provider, the ÚOHS will not remain inactive when it comes to rejecting (discriminating against) other interested parties.
And the Czechs will finally not make more expensive calls than the rest of Europe.
