The Prague transport companies will also transport on a chip for the first time on Wednesday
Wednesday, October 1, 2008, will enter the history of the Prague transport companies as a date on which the first passengers, instead of a paper ticket, will enter the subway, tram or bus, who will carry an electronic coupon in their pocket.
These can currently buy about one hundred thousand people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can buy a 30-day, 90-day or annual oupon (valid from 1 January 2009) and can play it on their chip card at the same time, in the information centres and branches of the transport companies at the metro stations Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letany, Kobylsy, Rajská taurada, Kačerov and Luka.
Since yesterday the coupons are also available on the Internet on the pages of the transport companies www.dpp.cz.
The service was used by more than four hundred customers until the afternoon hours.
Those who use the Internet sales can really forget the output window in the subway stations, where they have to wait regularly for their paper tickets in long queues.
They buy the coupon over the Internet, it is recorded on the Opencard in one of the thirteen branches of the city library.
"At these places, the traveller is also available a switch with trained staff, who advises interested parties when buying the internet and also plays the coupon on the map," says the speaker of the Martin Opatrný project.
In addition to the libraries, the electronic coupons can also be played on self-control machines on the open card, which are installed in some underground vestibüls.
What do those machines look like?
They are red, they are reminiscent of a ticket, the passengers may have noticed them at the Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská metro stations.
"At the moment there are five of them in the city, but by the end of the year it should be eighty," adds Opatrný.
The coupon controls a machine instead of the driver
The operation of the machines, which will work from tomorrow, is easy.
All you have to do is enter the chip card, and the previously acquired coupon is on your own.
The electronic coupons will apply from tomorrow not only in the capital but also in the surrounding area.
So in the suburbs and on the bus lines with the numbers 300 to 499, with which the inhabitants of the municipalities of the region of Central Bohemia in particular get to the capital.
"In the trains that belong to the Prague integrated transport, the train attendants have reading equipment with which they can check the validity of the coupons after time and zone," explains Filip Drápal of the Ropid organisation. This organisation sets up the timetables for the Prague transport companies.
The suburban buses have card reading equipment at the checkout at the driver's place.
When entering, the chip card must not only be shown to the driver, but the Opencard must be placed at a marked point on the side of the checkout.
The driver controls the validity of the recorded coupons.
"If a passenger wants to check the validity of the recorded coupons, nothing is easier than to ask the driver for this information," Drápal said.
