Let's take the example of "Sixth Street Prep," a primary school in eastern Los Angeles.
The majority of the students are Hispanic and come from low-income families.
More than one third of the students, many of whom have recently been in the country, learn English.
However, in 2008, an amazing 100% of fourth-class students passed the state exam in Mathe at a good level.
Also surprisingly, 93% of the children from the fourth year of school were rated as good in the English exam.
This amazing success has been achieved with other methods than those that Obama prefers.
The school Sixth Street places its focus on review and exercise, on constant control of knowledge and a attitude that does not tolerate any exceptions.
The school also practices the approach to training in an English-speaking environment, which is exactly what Obama should be aware of, says the head of the school Linda Mikkel.
This approach places emphasis on the almost exclusive use of the English language in technical education.
Mrs Mikkel, who rejected the idea of bilingual training, said to me that the school had a remarkable success with a student who had just come from Mexico. 12 months later, one would be able to enter the classroom and not recognize it.
"It works," she said, "it works for us."
Would Obama take a school like the Sixth Street Prep as a model for other schools with a large share of Latin American and other English students?
The school's services would make the answer to this question easy, but the educational positions within its own party (the national education associations have long supported the idea of bilingual training) and its own consistent support for bilingual training make predictions about Obama's response uncertain.
While agreeing to the point that immigrants should learn English, he recently trivialized the subject by noting that people should stop worrying about the legislation aimed at "only English."
Instead, he said, "I want you to make sure your child can have Spanish."
If Obama really wants to close the performance gap, he should take careful account of educational models that work instead of despising and trivialising them.
