Isabel Bayón calls back the memory of the dancer from Seville Tórtola Valencia
A flamenco dancer from Seville adore a dancer who also came from Seville.
Carmen Tórtola Valencia: her father was Catalan (Florenç Tórtola Ferrer) and the mother of Andalusian (Georgina Valencia Valenzuela), she was born in the Triana district and when she was three years old her family moved to London.
She was a dancer and expert in oriental dances.
She had an exciting life, she was one of the first women to fight for the emancipation of the woman, such as Isadora Ducan, Virginia Woolf or Sarah Bernhardt.
She was a Buddhist, vegetarian, and was in favour of the abolition of the corset, which restricted the free female movement.
The life of this woman, who left her mark in the dance and aesthetic revolution in Europe in the time between the wars, fascinated Isabel Bayón.
"I wanted to work with Pepa Gamboa and she proposed this role to me, which seemed impossible to me."
'We are not trying to tell about her life, without her esprit, 'said the Flamencotanzerin.
Your dance grounds have helped me a lot in Flamenco.
"The dance of the butterfly" was like Guajira, for example, or "the dance of the snake" like Tango.
Her dancing was sensual and I was told that my dancing is also in this aesthetic area ', she says.
The production expects two extraordinary works: with Miguel Poveda, who will sing again for Isabel at one of her ideas, as he did in 'La puerta abierta'; and with Flamenco-master Matilde Coral, who wanted to work with one of her ex-students for the time being.
'Matilde plays Tórtola, a very mature personality.
I'm happy because she agreed to participate in my work, and I feel very honored. '
The production also takes place with musical composition and the guitarists Jesús Torres and Paco Arriaga, with the song of Miguel Ortega, el Pulga and Moi de Morón; with the percussion of El Pájaro, as well as the viola of Rafa el Viola and the collaboration with the actor Juanfra Júarez, he 'takes over the role of the director of the artists who were Divas, in whom he always falls in love.'
In this work, we also talk in a certain way about this woman's life, which has become known in places as far as India, the United States or Russia, and also throughout Europe, although she has normally lived in London.
"I wanted to recall her, because I think she is one of the women who has an enormous influence on a particular era and whose works today no longer have any value for her," says Bayón.
