The drivers, who can be lost due to the alcohol level, will have to install the 'Alcolock'.
The Authority orders that the driver, who had three official penalties for the level of alcohol, install this system in his car, which prohibits him from starting the car in the drunk state. If he is alcoholic, the car does not start.
The initiative was announced last month in June and is already part of the report of the General Prosecutor, according to which it is a pilot project that will last for a year.
The purpose is to resocialize the driver, which is why he is given a course to retrain the traffic behaviour.
The Ministry of Transport and the Foundation of the Technical Institute for Safety of Automobiles will also participate in this, in addition to the General Prosecutor's Office, according to experience.
According to statistics, between 30-75% of the drivers, who were more than once shown for driving under alcohol influence, were driving again.
The 'alcolock' would prevent this because it is a system connected to the car, it measures the alcohol content in the air emitted and prevents car start when the driver has made an alcohol test; or if an alcohol concentration is found higher than allowed.
It costs more than EUR 1 000, the costs are borne by the person who imposed the penalty.
In this context, a study carried out in the US in 2007 has shown that cars equipped with these devices are already preventing up to 65% of the regulatory infringements in the first year following its introduction.
In Spain, 115 lives could be saved each year.
The measure is limited to the administrative sanctions for two reasons: to take this approach before it becomes a crime.
And in order to facilitate its implementation, a legal reform can be implemented in the ordinary way, and yet a reform of the basic law is required for the law enforcement process.
The device is still available in the Spanish markets, not in any business, although it has already been installed in some commercial vehicles and public transport vehicles.
The House of Representatives will vote tomorrow because of the initiative of the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party, which proposes to install this system in school buses, which has already been done in France.
