Discussion - From the blood that became safe again
Hema-Quebec celebrated the 10th anniversary of its foundation yesterday, and her President, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to be pleased, because Hema-Quebec has become one of the most secure and efficient blood banks in the world.
And above all, it has regained the public's confidence, which had been severely shaken by the scandal of the contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As you know, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross's blood donation service were contaminated with the HI virus and the hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In view of this tragedy and the dissatisfaction of the public, in February 1994 the Government of Canada launched a public investigation, led by Judge Horace Krever, to bring light to the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to draw up guidelines to prevent a new disaster of this kind.
While Judge Krever was still hesitant to report, several provinces set up a committee to develop a new system for the management of blood canned in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this task.
According to the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, which is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian blood company to provide the other provinces and the two territories.
In 1998, when Hema-Quebec started work, hardly 38% of the people had faith in the blood-conserving system in Quebec, Dr. Décary remembers.
The situation was discouraging.
By the enormous efforts to improve the safety of blood reserves and by working in this field over the following years, we have regained public confidence ', she says, before proudly stressing that in early 2008, almost 94% of the population of Quebec had had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
However, Dr. Décary is aware that "trust is something extremely fragile."
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, Hema-Quebec has been acting in accordance with the principle of caution.
At that time, we experienced the occurrence of many cases of the human form of the bovine insanity in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, tells this woman, who has been in charge since the foundation of 1998.
And we didn't have the slightest idea if this disease could be transmitted over the blood.
So we were referring to one of the main guidelines of the reports of Krever and Gélineau, which states that exclusion measures are applied if you do not know this and if a disease is only slowly progressing, as is obviously the case with Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is expressed by a degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
So in April 1999, no blood was taken from people who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago, no doubt, it was proven that this disease is being transmitted over the blood.
This event has shown us that the principle of caution we used has a meaning.
In 1999, a much more precise technology was published on the market for the detection of HIV: the NST, which allows to demonstrate the presence of the virus itself directly in the blood of the donor, and not the antibodies to the virus, as was the case with the tests used to date.
The NST made it possible to shorten the incubation time that takes place between the time the person was infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected by our techniques in the blood, explains the specialist.
This time could be reduced to less than a week.
The risk of some donors being infected without knowing it and not knowing it was significantly reduced.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of transferring AIDS through blood transfusion.
Today, one of 12 million people is at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
'In other words, it means that you have to distribute 12 million blood reserves before someone is infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood reserves every year, it would take more than 24 years for a case in which HIV was transmitted through a blood conserve.
I believe that today you can feel comfortable getting or prescribing a blood transfusion to restore health ', says Hema-Quebec's director.
'Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogens can get into the system.
Only last year on the island of Réunion the Chikungunya virus, which is transmitted through insects through the blood, as well as the Westnil virus.
We need to monitor continuously ', Dr. Décary continues before she stresses that Hema-Quebec must also provide sufficient supply in addition to a safe supply.
'The need is increasing because the population is ageing.
As cancer control treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has an impact on the blood donor network, which on average only 3% of the people in Quebec who are suitable for blood donation. '
In doing so, any healthy person who is 18 years or older and who meets the criteria of suitability can donate blood every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
On average, 14% of the people who provide their blood are not accepted because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and those who have travelled to a country where malaria is widespread are excluded from the blood donation for one year.
'With this 3% we manage to obtain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
The lack of supplies is very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor network when they get older and can no longer donate blood.
It is difficult to convince people to donate blood, but above all to keep them and make them become regular donors.
Life is so hectic these days that it is rare to find the time to spend an hour of blood donation ', Francine Décary regrets.
With an annual budget of 297 million dollars, Hema-Quebec not only supplies blood conserved, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, heart flaps, eyeballs and skin, which is almost exclusively used in severe fire injuries.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before being stored at Hema-Quebec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord, which was previously considered a biomedical waste, contains rich blood stem cells that can serve to treat severe diseases such as leukaemia.
'A few weeks ago we celebrated the storage of our thousands of umbilical cord blood samples, and we plan to decrease more than a thousand per year.
'We should probably start at the beginning of next year to make it available for transplants', explains Dr. Décary, who describes this program of the umbilical cord loss as very popular.
'Many mothers are convinced not to have access to it 'because Hema-Quebec lacks the means to offer this complex and expensive program in all hospitals.
