The psychology of overbidding - or why we are willing to pay more
In the case of auctions, the buyers tend to spend more and thus overvalue the file.
Neurologists and economic researchers at the University of New York have now been able to discover the neurological and economic foundations of this well-known and seemingly irrational behaviour.
According to a study published in the "Science" magazine, people do not want to be beaten in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even higher prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers should play lotto while the other took part in a playful action - in both cases the active brain regions of the subjects were examined by means of functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games the participants were able to win money, but an increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the brain, was measured in the loss of the auction, in which the adversary's overbidding plays an essential role.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-reward" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore considered that the price increase could be explained by the prevention of an overreaction of the striatum.
In order to support their thesis, the economists in the research group have also done research on the follow-up of the money.
In this case, three groups should be involved against a partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product, after which they made their bets.
Another group was also promised a $15 reward in case they came out of the game as winners.
The third group received $15 before the auction, which was also lost in the event of a lost game.
So the difference between the two groups was that the emphasis was on one on winning, while the other on losing.
However, as evidence of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, the members of the "against losing" group were ready for higher stakes than those in the control group or the "profit" group.
"These results cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
These have so far only justified the behaviour observed in auctions with the joy of winning or avoiding risk.
The contradiction between these two theories was resolved thanks to the imaging neurological procedures, so that we now have a third explanation ready "- said Andrew Schotter, Professor of the Business Faculty of the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should the doctor be visited?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected people is estimated to be hundreds of thousands in this country, but only seven thousand are treated, which is because patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver diseases caused by various viruses.
The symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and the diseases differ.
Depending on the disease, the hepatic viruses spread in two different ways: in hepatitis A and E by the digestive tract (for example by contaminated food or water), in hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted by blood and other body fluids (such as sperm, secretion or saliva).
Travelers are recommended to vaccinate against viruses A and B in any case, and there is no vaccine against virus C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A are approximately two to three weeks after the consumption of the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and vomiting.
Then the jaundice occurs on the skin and in the eyes, the chair becomes bright, the urine dark, and the recovery can last for up to two-three weeks.
Around 1 million people die every year from the far more severe diseases caused by hepatitis B, such as liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only every tenth infected person is in medical treatment.
Hepatitis C may also have serious consequences: it may lead to liver cirrhosis and liver cancer without treatment.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, as the pathogen surgically destroys the liver cells - in many cases the first symptoms show up after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular controls, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease is more common: those who have had blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattoos.
At present, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease is already detectable in a routine laboratory study, it is advisable to visit the doctor at the first signs of unknown origin.
In time, the disease is cured, the virus can be eradicated, thus eliminating the risk of infection and preventing the development of cancer.
September 30 is the world day of hepatitis, for the first time organized by patient representatives worldwide.
The aim of the action is to raise awareness of this chronic inflammation of the liver caused by viruses, their origin and the importance of early detection.
Do believers have less pain?
As the latest research results show, religious faith is like a kind of "painkillers," which should have already facilitated the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University have carried out an interesting experiment: it has been studied to what extent faith in God affects the sense of pain of man, the British paper "Telegraph."
In the course of the rather bizarre investigation, 12 believers and atheists each received electric shocks while studying a painting by the Mother of God.
As the results showed, the faithful were able to take out most of the pain.
A brain scan technology even proved that Catholics could activate the part of their brain that is responsible for pain control.
The research was the first in a research project in which, in addition to scientists, philosophers and theologians from various departments of the university also participate.
When the subjects were tried, a radiant device was connected to the left hand, which gave off the electric shocks.
The participants were asked to focus heavily on two paintings: one is a picture of the Mother of God, painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century, and the other is Leonardo da Vinci's "Lady with Hermelin."
The researchers hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary among the faithful would create a kind of religious trance while choosing Vinci's image, because it was hardly different from the other painting and felt reassuring.
The subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and at that time they received a total of 20 electric shocks in four stages, while they should either look at the religious or the other painting.
The Catholics reported that at the sight of the Mother of God they felt "safe" as if they were "worried about" and they felt "peace and peace."
