Intelligent car imitates the flight of the Hummel
What would be the best way to develop new technologies to prevent accidents, if not to imitate the obstacle sensors from nature?
For example, the bees.
At the CEATEC in Japan an amazing project was presented, in which the Nissan engineers of Hummeln were inspired in the creation of new accident-avoiding systems.
In cooperation with the Tokyo University, Nissan has built the BR23C-type biomimetic system controlled by car robots, a mini-car equipped with the characteristics of the bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collision.
In the flight, each bee forms its own, oval "private area," which is very similar to our own "shield," said Kazuhhiro Doi, product manager for technology PR and research development, at the exhibition.
The composite eye of the bee, which can see in any direction and at an angle of over 300 degrees, plays an important role in this.
In order to imitate the function of the composite eye, the researchers took up the idea of the laser-controlled distance meter.
This identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C in a 180-degree field of vision within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor to board, which immediately initiates the collision-avoiding process.
The obstacle is recorded in seconds, and the car robot immediately changes the course, similar to the movement of the bees by turning the tires around the appropriate angle.
Unlike previous systems, this maneuver is purely instinctive.
"If not, the car robot could not react quickly enough to avoid the obstacles," said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the "Mobility Laboratory" and the car robot project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the inner and most vulnerable part of the shield - a layer within which accidents are still considered to be inevitable.
The whole process must reflect the behaviour of the bees when they avoid other bees.
And this has to be done in a fraction of a second.
However, in contrast to the bees, it is not possible to go up, down, or even diagonal - it can only be two-dimensional, only towards the weathering of the tyres.
While the bees are at an infinitely wide range of possibilities to avoid other bees, the researchers in the car engine were able to use only the rotary movement, or the acceleration and deceleration.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy efficient and therefore have a longer life life than conventional lithium ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it depends on the instinctive, intelligent reaction, and less on the processing of the data, and even less on the ability to store it.
This device must only process a few inputs per second and respond accordingly to them.
It does not have to save these, or produce an intuitive, logical reaction on the basis of previous maneuvers, so that it is constantly using only a handful of KB memory.
There is no need for gigabytes and megabytes of severe memories.
This is the first step in the development of immediate collision prevention technology, which Nissan considers to be in production as standard within the next ten years.
Another application could find the technology in GPS satellite navigation by consciously directing the driver around obstacles and thus leading him to the goal.
