Students Victims of up to 900 Euro per room high rental prices
The market for apartments for students does not know any crises.
According to the last study of the Sunia, the rental union, a single room can cost a student up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples and 600 in Rome.
"This phenomenon has already taken on very serious features. The whole range of students lose their right to study in such a way that their families are unable to support them at this level" - said Sunia, Laura Mariani - "in these cities, the great demand from students leads to a deformation of the market that has also damaged the other inhabitants.
In addition, most of the rent offers include a number of infringements: free contracts, missing registrations, no rent price limit, unauthorized underrent.
For the Sunia there is a need for exceptional measures, which result in lower rental prices through a revision of the tax.
The study shows that in Milan a sleeping area in the Brianza area is needed about 450 euros; a single room starts at 650 euros (in the Bande Nere district) and ends with 800 euros in the Lambiate, Udine and Fiera district or even 900 euros in the Vittoria area.
In Florence, a sleeping area costs an average of 350 / 400 euros, a room 700.
In Bologna, where the students concentrate in the quarters around the university, there are 250 / 280 euros for a place to sleep, 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome, the prices in the quarters around the university are about 600 euros for a single room, 450 for a sleeping area in a double room.
Only a little deeper are the rent in the quarters around the other universities of Rome: 550 euros in Ostiense and Cinecittà.
Only those who emigrate in outdoor areas can save money: 300 euros for a sleeping area and 450 euros for a single room in Prenestina, Centacelle and similar quarters.
In Naples you need 300-450 euros for a sleeping area, for one room the price is between 400 and 600 euros in the most expensive quarters, the Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei.
In Bari, a sleeping area costs 250-350 euros, a single room at least 350 euros.
In the smallest cities, prices are lower, but they have a greater weight in the urban economy.
In the cities where the phenomenon of renting to non-European students is more common, such as Perugia, there is even another anomaly: a 25-30% higher than average rent is required by foreign students.
Goodbye to the old cinema Paradiso - the cities close their historical cinema halls
The historical cinemas close due to the beneficiary multiplex cinemas.
"A city without cinema is a blind city, like a face without eyes."
This picture of the director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is currently happening in the large urban centres of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of exclusion of cinemas, which began with the birth of the large multiroom complex in the periphery, means in the long term death for the single-room cinema in the centre. A process that does not only seem inevitable and irrevocable, but also bears the traits of a cultural crime.
"It is like losing a friend with whom you have laid a piece of street full of emotions," says the director of the film "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso," who brought him the Oskar and the Grand Prix of Cannes 20 years ago. It is the story of a suburban cinema and its nostalgia, which consists of living in a well-lost cinema world.
The figures provided by the Anec, the central trade association, speak a clear language: in the last five years, the enormous amount of 316 traditional cinemas have had to close; the majority of these have paid cinemas in the major cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
The most affected regions include Emilia-Romagna with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This shows that the main culprits are the multiplexkinos, because they are just these three regions in which the largest number of these modern cinemas has been registered: at 195 in the last 5 years, Lombardy has been leading the lists, 81 are both in Tuscany and in Emilia-Romagna.
"The business has developed in an irrational way," says Paolo Protti, the president of the Anec, "it is useful that new structures also arise, but the first thing is to maintain the existing one, because a room in the city is closed, not all of its regular customers are ready to visit a multiplexino in the periphery instead of the old one.
And here the missing budget for the association's fund remains outside of eight: the debt burden recorded by the state is about EUR 10 million.
It is a shame from the ethical-moral point of view that the government does not respect the existing laws.
To maintain the sector would be between 16 and 18 million euros a year of need. "
The case of Bologna, the first Italian city, which has decided to protect it by means of an agreement between the municipality and the Anec due to the fears of the old cinema, is the first such agreement in Italy to protect and support traditional cinemas, both in the historical centre and in the periphery.
The measures envisaged include tax incentives for cinema operators as well as benefits for the public in terms of local transport: it will be possible to drive to the traffic-limited areas of the centre and to park at more favourable parking charges.
"It is a pleasant initiative," said Giuseppe Tornatore, "I hope that other cities will join us and also develop new concepts.
But we certainly need better audio and video equipment to be able to do something against the superpower of the multiplex rooms, because the audience of today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema has always been an important issue for me: the closure of the "supercinema" of Baghiera, the place of my childhood and youth, was the crucial point that made me start the "Nuovo cinema paradise," even though I had been playing with the thought for 10 years.
For 25 years I have lived in Rome; if I pass by the Rialto or the Quirinale in Via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn my side to not have to see the dust-covered posters.
