When the energy comes out of the waves, the big ones suddenly run up
It is a non-fading source of money that covers more than 70% of the planet's surface and only now seems to understand this by the great energy companies in the world.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that are now all looking at, and are also looking to occupiate, such as giants like Chevron.
The possibility of gaining energy from the movements of the sea has been considered and investigated for 70 years, and these studies have not been significantly intensified since the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil broke in around 1980, the idea of marine energy was lost, but now the environmental organisations and the increased price of oil are pushing for new impetus in this sector.
The World Energy Council in London estimates that 15% of the world's energy needs could be covered by the energy produced by the ocean waves.
This would be equal to double the energy currently produced by nuclear power plants.
The currents and tides would also be added.
Giants in the attack.
The first company that now relies on marine energy is Enersis, who signed a contract in 2005 for the construction of a power plant in northern Portugal.
When this message was published, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, there are now more and more companies from the traditional energy industry that rely on marine energy production.
"Chevron is investigating these technologies," says the spokesperson of a company known to the American giants in the Wall Street Journal, and is considering the possibility of working with us. "
This is about obtaining an authorisation from the American Energy Commission, which is necessary to launch a project off the coast of Alaska.
This is a not-to-be-underestimated sign, given that, in Alaska, oil is still being promoted by the US and President Bush has recently launched the plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, the companies Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey are also investing in the new industry; if the details are not known, observers are talking about an increasing interest.
Even better-looking technologies.
Experts are talking about a technology that is still in progress, not least because the last doubts have not yet been resolved by the environmentalists.
So far, projects such as those in Portugal and Scotland are of a rather small dimension and do not seem to cause any serious environmental problems.
However, in order to produce large-scale energy, technologies with far greater environmental impact are needed.
There are various ways: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of connected bojen.
The thrust of the waves, which moves the bowls up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure within the swimmers via flasks and cylinders.
This drives a turbine, which in turn operates a generator.
The electricity is sent to the coast via underwater lines.
So far there are four planned installations of this kind, which are only waiting for state approval. Part of the energy obtained could also be used for military facilities.
Verdant Power, however, already produces energy for a building of goods and a parking lot with the help of underground turbines in the East River of New York.
The water movements during the tides drive the turbines, which feed the generator through the resulting rotation.
According to Verdant, a long line of potential clients is waiting for the necessary authorisations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute for Power-winning Research, a special interest is currently worthy of the potential that is in the tides.
Although this is also an irregular phenomenon, the tides are better predictable than wind currents, solar radiation and also waves, and therefore a more reliable source of electricity.
It is precisely the tidal energy that led states such as New York, Maine and Alaska and other coastal states to invest $7.5 million in 2008 - up to 35 million are already planned for 2009.
